40abb4f7d73ceadf087e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c41ab4521c4c2b6bde7b03ec4d9531acdc101f7e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a545f286136f5024bdadaa47d305e437cf32614f.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" Context Stores \n As any workflow usually operates with data, you need some kind of temporary \u201Cmemory\u201D to store that data. In ORIGAM, such a data repository is called a  Context store . \n Context stores take care of all data used across your workflow, and you need to create at least one. A Context store can be based on XML and linked to a specific Data Structure, which defines its structural content, or be a simple value defined by the data type (e.g. integer, date, string). \n To create a new Context store, right-click on your workflow (either the box in the diagram editor or the workflow name in the Model Browser tree) and select new  Context Store : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/36c54bed2d553b62a3b0e4257089980d8d3b8baa.png]\nDescription: The image features a user interface element labeled \u0022TakeOverTasks\u0022 with accompanying text that reads \u0022Right click here to add steps.\u0022 A right-click context menu is displayed, showcasing options including \u0022Delete,\u0022 \u0022New,\u0022 and \u0022Actions.\u0022 Under the \u0022New\u0022 option, various task types are listed, such as \u0022(Task) Service Method Call,\u0022 \u0022(Task) User Interface,\u0022 \u0022(Task) Workflow Call,\u0022 \u0022(Task) Set Workflow Property,\u0022 and \u0022(Task) Update context by Xpath,\u0022 among others. The \u0022Context Store\u0022 is highlighted within the menu options, indicating its selection. The apparent purpose of the image is to illustrate a programming or task management interface where users can define and manage tasks within a system.\n\n\n  \n In the editor, select your Data Structure \u2014 in this example, we use  Task  \u2014 and save it. The Context store name will be set automatically based on the Data Structure name: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/2047fd753cbc4e0a208f16a39738bf3a505a2196.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a Context Store management tool, specifically focused on a schema item labeled \u0022Task.\u0022 The panel is organized into two main sections: Info and Misc. The Info section includes columns with headers for \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 and \u0022Name,\u0022 showing values of empty, False, and \u0022Task,\u0022 respectively. The Misc section includes fields such as \u0022DataType\u0022 (set to Xml), \u0022DefaultSet\u0022 (False), \u0022DisableConstraints\u0022 (False), \u0022IsReturnValue\u0022 (False), \u0022RuleSet,\u0022 and a field labeled \u0022Structure.\u0022 This interface appears to be used for configuring or managing context schema attributes related to tasks within a data service or application.\n\n\n  \n Notes: \n \n One Context store can be based on a single data structure, but that structure may contain multiple entities. \n In some cases you may need to set  DisableConstraints  to  True , because if any required field is left blank in any of the workflow steps \u2013 before saving the entire record, an error would otherwise occur. \n \n This is the workflow diagram editor with a new Context store created: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/608ee9ae39b661b94dc476d2dd0d4be6e0a18f72.png]\nDescription: The interface displays a module titled \u0022TakeOverTasks\u0022 at the top. Below the title, there is a button labeled \u0022Task\u0022 featuring an icon of a home or navigation symbol next to it. The layout suggests this is part of a task management application, likely for managing or taking over tasks within a system. The design is simple and functional, focusing on task navigation.\n\n\n  \n If you haven\u2019t done it earlier, you can now set up tracing for your workflow, as you may need it later. \n Double-click on the workflow header and configure it: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c31a1524164812eb45347515973b898f2d4ffa47.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a Sequential Workflow titled \u0022TakeOverTasks.\u0022 It includes a section labeled \u0022(Info)\u0022 with subfields for \u0022Schema Item,\u0022 showing values for \u0022Ancestors\u0022 (False), \u0022Inheritability\u0022 (False), and \u0022Name\u0022 (TakeOverTasks). The \u0022Tracing\u0022 section has two entries: \u0022Trace\u0022 (Yes) and \u0022Trace Level\u0022 (Yes). The layout suggests that this interface is used for configuring or managing a workflow, specifically regarding its schema and tracing options.\n\n\n","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:02:37"},"vector":[-0.0027895253,-0.034944825,-0.06291835,0.02703676,0.010571217,-0.028321207,-0.02068391,0.029310687,0.031092362,0.001239933,0.003163269,-0.038584255,0.004017567,0.027332384,0.011709321,0.016660746,-0.009247201,-0.013890128,0.0013104768,0.0010403624,-0.00025764215,-0.020518858,0.043387618,-0.00870345,0.011992381,0.04835523,-0.015284337,-0.029260155,-0.022776658,-0.0013977146,0.0020867647,-0.022492746,0.035610244,-0.0016924473,0.018034656,-0.003076425,0.004821915,0.002673141,-0.028243687,0.023841936,-0.0017882381,-0.0062550292,0.0046631433,0.0074535394,0.008753594,-0.031527538,0.01142058,-0.004306888,-0.0051783873,-0.075650305,-0.051502403,-0.008135271,0.024734039,-0.026766213,0.03034853,0.057120048,-0.074472435,-0.04746195,-0.0652008,-0.0003276876,-0.022427842,-0.015727716,-0.016696716,0.0019033134,-0.00076327426,0.006567129,-0.00477281,0.015691912,-0.005721665,-0.02285323,0.0208383,0.0264964,-0.071128055,-0.042230956,-0.03506587,-0.019209972,-0.02905939,-0.0033237739,-0.018124